{
  "answer": "**The work is *San Hyan Mahajnana* (unknown author; Kawi original, English translation), Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis Shaiva tantric text compares **puruṣa** (the Self or pure consciousness, trapped in the ocean of *saṃsāra* or worldly suffering) to a **nāga** (serpent) terrified in the midst of dangerous waters.[^2] The sacred syllable **oṃkāra** is identified as **Garuḍa** (the mythical bird and enemy of serpents), which swoops down to rescue it, lifting the serpent-Self upward to **śivapada** (the abode of Shiva).[^3]\n\nThe verse is:  \n*In the terrible ocean of saṃsāra, puruṣa is situated like a nāga. Knowing oṃkāra to be Garuḍa [...] for the effort [...] // 64*[^4]\n\nThe key prose explication follows immediately:  \n\"The likeness of the revered *puruṣa* is one who is in the middle of the waters, terrified like a serpent. The holy *oṃkāra* is named Garuḍa. He is the one who brings the revered *puruṣa* to *śivapada*.\"[^5]\n\nA nearby prose line reinforces *oṃkāra*'s role: \"In the heart, there is what is called *śivapada* (the abode of Shiva). The holy *oṃkāra* is the supreme void, very subtle.\"[^6]\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1 (slug: `01`), [translation](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/).\n[^2]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [p-7b2370](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-7b2370).\n[^3]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [p-d9dbdf](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-d9dbdf).\n[^4]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [p-7b2370](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-7b2370).\n[^5]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [paragraphs p-7b2370 to p-d9dbdf](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-7b2370).\n[^6]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [p-100b1c](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-100b1c).",
